Back in April 2022, Warner Bros. Discovery came into the world
with a slew of near-existential disadvantages=E2=80=94the company was burde=
ned by a $55 billion debt load, a BBB credit rating, and a rocky operating =
environment for its array of linear TV offerings, cable channels, and Holly=
wood fare. The equity markets didn=E2=80=99t look kindly upon the Frankenmo=
nster that David Zaslav had created through Discovery Communications, his c=
hallenged business, and the vestiges of AT&T=E2=80=99s Warner Media. Since =
the company=E2=80=99s formation, the stock is down 55 percent.
The S&P 500 has risen 20 percent during the same time period.

=C2=A0

And yet if WBD=E2=80=99s fourth quarter 2024 performance is a harbinger of =
things to come, the worst may be over. I=E2=80=99ve long argued that WBD is=
 really a publicly traded leveraged buyout, and the key to unlocking value =
was the simultaneous servicing of its debt=E2=80=94an objective that Zaz ha=
s been highly incentivized to achieve=E2=80=94in lockstep with the
growth of its direct-to-consumer business and overall profitability. At som=
e point, I=E2=80=99ve contended, the company would pay down enough debt and=
 make enough cash (and project the ability to rev up on both fronts) that i=
nvestors would look past the ominous headlines about its declining cable as=
sets, its forfeiture of the NBA, and challenges in the film division.

=C2=A0

It looks like we=E2=80=99ve now reached an inflection point. Net debt at
WBD is at $34.6 billion=E2=80=94$40 billion of gross debt, less $5.4 of cas=
h and cash equivalents=E2=80=94and the company=E2=80=99s leverage ratio of =
3.8x adjusted EBITDA is on its way to a ratio of 2.5x-3x gross leverage. Me=
anwhile, Max is growing, and Zaz has signaled harder than ever that he=E2=
=80=99s willing to kill his darlings from Discovery. =E2=80=9CD.T.C. net ad=
ds and EBITDA continue to shine,=E2=80=9D Kutgun Maral, at Evercore ISI, wr=
ote in a quick note after the earnings release on Thursday.

The $3 Billion Improvement
--------------------------

Indeed, WBD has paid down $19 billion of its debt load in nearly
three years. =E2=80=9CWe will continue to be super, super focused on this,=
=E2=80=9D C.F.O. Gunnar Wiedenfels said during the company=E2=80=99s earnin=
gs call on Thursday morning. As I=E2=80=99ve reported before, the tenor of =
the WBD debt is also quite advantageous to the company, at least in the cur=
rent interest-rate environment. At the end of December, the average maturit=
y of the company=E2=80=99s remaining debt was 13.4 years, at an average int=
erest rate cost of 4.7 percent. That=E2=80=99s tasty for a company with a B=
BB
credit rating, considering the yield on the 10-year Treasury is currently 4=
=2E2 percent.

=C2=A0

WBD does have some near-term debt maturities, including $2.2 billion due in=
 March, which explains the company=E2=80=99s logic for carrying $5.4 billio=
n in cash on its balance sheet. On the earnings call, Gunnar said the balan=
ce sheet is in =E2=80=9Cvery good shape now=E2=80=9D and that he is not wor=
ried about any near-term debt maturities. =E2=80=9CI
view our capital structure as a real asset,=E2=80=9D he said. I don=E2=80=
=99t know when, or if, the credit rating agencies will upgrade WBD=E2=80=99=
s BBB credit rating. But when they do=E2=80=94and it should be soon(ish), I=
 would think=E2=80=94that will be the day the rocket fuel gets injected int=
o the WBD publicly traded L.B.O. (This is not investment advice.)

=C2=A0

This isn=E2=80=99t just a balance sheet narrative, however. WBD has achieve=
d a fair amount of
success in the fastest growing parts of the business. Zaz=E2=80=99s strateg=
y of internationalizing Max, WBD=E2=80=99s direct-to-consumer offering, see=
ms to be paying off. Total D.T.C. subscribers reached 117 million in the fo=
urth quarter, with the majority of those subs, nearly 60 million, coming fr=
om outside the United States. After penetrating Latin America, the service =
now has toeholds in the U.K., Ireland, Australia, Germany, and Italy. =E2=
=80=9CMax became one of the very few global scaled and profitable streaming
services,=E2=80=9D the company wrote in a letter to shareholders that accom=
panied the earnings report.

There was also unexpected subscriber growth in the U.S., with some 4.5 mill=
ion new subscribers domestically, as compared to analysts expectations of 2=
=2E8 million. =E2=80=9CThe U.S. is a pr=
etty mature market,=E2=80=9D Zaz said.=
 =E2=80=9CWe think that there=E2=80=99s still some growth, given the qualit=
y of our service, and we=E2=80=99re fighting for that.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile, =
streaming is now solidly profitable at WBD. In
the fourth quarter, D.T.C. adjusted EBITDA=E2=80=94I hate that term, as Zaz=
 knows=E2=80=94was $409 million, up from a loss in the fourth quarter of 20=
23 and above the $275 million that Wall Street was expecting, as Maral wrot=
e in his note. For all of 2024, D.T.C.=E2=80=99s adjusted EBITDA was $677 m=
illion, up exponentially from $103 million in 2023.=C2=A0

