;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Back in April 2022, Warner Bros. Discovery=
 came into the world
with a slew of near-existential disadvantages=E2=80=94the company was burde=
ned by a $55 billion debt load, a BBB credit rating, and a rocky operating =
environment for its array of linear TV offerings, cable channels, and Holly=
wood fare. The equity markets didn=E2=80=99t look kindly upon the Frankenmo=
nster that <strong>David Zaslav </strong>had created through Discovery Comm=
unications, his challenged business, and the vestiges of AT&amp;T=E2=80=99s=
 Warner Media. Since the company=E2=80=99s formation, the stock is down 55 =
percent.
The S&amp;P 500 has risen 20 percent during the same time period.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">And yet if WBD=E2=80=99s fourth quarter 2024 performance is a ha=
rbinger of things to come, the worst may be over. I=E2=80=99ve long argued =
that WBD is really a publicly traded leveraged buyout, and the key to unloc=
king value was the simultaneous servicing of its debt=E2=80=94an objective =
that Zaz has been <em>highly </em>incentivized to achieve=E2=80=94in lockst=
ep with the
growth of its direct-to-consumer business and overall profitability. At som=
e point, I=E2=80=99ve contended, the company would pay down enough debt and=
 make enough cash (and project the ability to rev up on both fronts) that i=
nvestors would look past the ominous headlines about its declining cable as=
sets, its forfeiture of the NBA, and challenges in the film division.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">It =
looks like we=E2=80=99ve now reached an inflection point. Net debt at
WBD is at $34.6 billion=E2=80=94$40 billion of gross debt, less $5.4 of cas=
h and cash equivalents=E2=80=94and the company=E2=80=99s leverage ratio of =
3.8x adjusted EBITDA is on its way to a ratio of 2.5x-3x gross leverage. Me=
anwhile, Max is growing, and Zaz has signaled harder than ever that he=E2=
=80=99s willing to kill his darlings from Discovery. =E2=80=9CD.T.C. net ad=
ds and EBITDA continue to shine,=E2=80=9D <strong>Kutgun Maral</strong>, at=
 Evercore ISI, wrote in a quick note after the earnings release on Thursday=
=2E</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
